wg <- scan("analysis/season/high-expression-winter-genes",what="character")

Order the Date factor by date and not alphabetically

dates <- rev(unique(as.character(samples$Date)))
dates <- dates[c(3:23,1,2)]
for(r in dates){
  samples$Date <- relevel(samples$Date,r)
}

3 Process

stopifnot(all(colnames(vst.mod) == rownames(samples)))
phloem.mat <- vst.mod[phloem,samples$Tissue=="Phloem"]

xylem.mat <- vst.mod[xylem,samples$Tissue=="Xylem"]

3.1 Phloem

3.1.1 Cluster

phloem.hc <- hclust(dist(t(phloem.mat)))
phloem.ct <- cutree(phloem.hc,5)
plot(phloem.hc,labels = samples[phloem.hc$labels,"Date"])

phloem.tp <- factor(phloem.ct,labels=c("Summer","Summer-early-late","Autumn","Winter","Spring"))
phloem.es <- expressionSpecificity(phloem.mat,as.character(phloem.tp),mode = "local",output="complete")
## Calculating tissue specificity

The genes are very ubiquitous

par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,3.1,0.1))
barplot(table(cut(phloem.es[,"score"],10)),las=2,main="Phloem tissue specificity")

barplot(table(cut(phloem.es[,"score"],10)),las=2,main="Phloem tissue specificity",log="y")

Interestingly the more expressed genes are the most ubiquitous

par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,3.1,0.1))
boxplot(split(phloem.es[,2:6],cut(phloem.es[,"score"],10)),las=2)

How many genes are not expressed across a season

pander(round(colSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6])) / nrow(phloem.es) * 100,2))
Autumn Spring Summer Summer-early-late Winter
1.25 1.42 0.29 0.18 1.98

How expressed are the NA containing genes (max expression)

boxplot(list(na.containing=phloem.es[rowSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6]))>=1,"maxn"],
             no.na=phloem.es[rowSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6]))==0,"maxn"]))

Obviously the expression levels is inversely proportional to the number of NAs

boxplot(split(phloem.es[rowSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6]))>=1,"maxn"],
              rowSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6]))[rowSums(is.na(phloem.es[,2:6]))>=1]))

Check for winter specific genes

dev.null <- sapply(levels(phloem.tp),function(tp){
  sel <- phloem.es[,tp] == phloem.es[,"maxn"]
  message(sprintf("There are %s genes with an expression peak in %s",
                  sum(sel,na.rm=TRUE),tp))
  par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,3.1,0.1))
  barplot(table(cut(phloem.es[sel,"score"],10)),las=2,
          main=paste0("Phloem ",tp," gene specificity"))
})
## There are 10040 genes with an expression peak in Summer
## There are 2948 genes with an expression peak in Summer-early-late

## There are 5233 genes with an expression peak in Autumn

## There are 9462 genes with an expression peak in Winter

## There are 6283 genes with an expression peak in Spring

w.genes <- phloem.es[phloem.es[,"Winter"] == phloem.es[,"maxn"] & !is.na(phloem.es[,"Winter"]),]
w.genes <- cbind(w.genes,lfc=w.genes[,"Winter"] - apply(w.genes[,c(2:5)],1,max))

Most of the genes identified as being only highly expressed in winter are present among the phloem winter specific genes

table(wg %in% rownames(w.genes))
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##    23   455
p.wg <- wg[wg %in% rownames(w.genes)]

Plot the expression change vs.Â the expression specificity The winter highly expressed genes are distributed all over.

heatscatter(w.genes[,"lfc"],w.genes[,"score"],
            ylab="seasonal expression specificity",xlab="log fold change winter - max(other seasons)")
abline(v=2,lty=2,col="gray")
abline(h=0.6,lty=2,col="gray")
points(w.genes[p.wg,"lfc"],w.genes[p.wg,"score"],col=2,pch=16)

the lfc can only be positive since these genes are most highly expressed in winter

phloem.winter.genes <- names(which(w.genes[,"score"]>0.6 & w.genes[,"lfc"]>=2))

message(sprintf("There are %s phloem genes that are winter specific",length(phloem.winter.genes)))
## There are 207 phloem genes that are winter specific
dir.create(file.path("analysis","season"),showWarnings = FALSE)
write(phloem.winter.genes,file = "analysis/season/phloem.winter.genes")
